t remember exactly when my father was born, but he was older than my mother, so by the time the War came, he was quite old. And the factory ran right through the War, but not making razor blades.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5975301 Ray:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 Ah!  So was it the war effort?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5975301 Ronald:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 It was a war factory, and - what was I going to say?  Yes, during the War, all razor blades, for whatever brand, were made by Gillette \endash 
 they were the only firm that were allowed to make razor blades during the War, in England. All the other razor blade factories made armaments, and that\rquote s what my father\rquote s factory did.  But he didn\rquote 
t realise that the man who managed it was, in fact, a German agent, until a long time after the War, when MI5 turned up in the shop one day, and said, \'93We\rquote ve got something to tell you\'94
, and showed him - and so Mr. Harkoff was [at last] dispatched the next day!
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5975301 Ray:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 But I\rquote m still struggling with your primary school!
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5975301 Ronald:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 Oh yes!  What happened at my primary scho
ol is a very nice story. Sorry, it got left out!  What happened was, my father thought it was important I should go to the same school as the neighbours\rquote 
 children, so I went to Beckford Road Infants School, and I was delivered there every morning by the ch
auffeur, in the car (LAUGHS), in the car, but just round the corner. Because Cricklewood was a very poor neighbourhood, apart from a few houses, and so most children were [literally] hardly dressed, actually, so I was a bit different from most of them.  A
nd it was the custom in the families - the well-off families, who were mostly Jewish - to send their children to the local primary school so they\rquote 
d kind of fit in, and one morning there was some confusion about my delivery at school, and although I eventually arrived, no one was quite sure how I\rquote d got there. It was a question of one of our neighbours\rquote 
 chauffeur and our chauffeur having done a deal that (LAUGHS) the other one would take me, and he took me. And something went wrong with my reception, [namely] that the teacher should have ticked me off, hadn\rquote 
t noticed. And so they phoned the house and said, maybe there was an odd item of clothing missing, or something like this. Anyway, the [outcome] was that it happened that I got taken home again by a neighbour\rquote 
s chauffeur in their car!  And then my father said, \'93Oh well, I\rquote ll take him back\'94, and that was the first time he\rquote 
d ever been to the school, and he was horrified because it was a very dirty, crummy school, and the whole place smelt of urine, a really stinky school.  And so my father said, \'93He\rquote s not going there any more\'94.  \'93
You will go to a private school\'94.  So my brother arranged \endash  he was the only with [a higher] education in the family \endash  my brother said, \'93Highgate is supposed to be very good.  Let\rquote s send him to Highgate Junior School\'94
. So I went to Highgate, to the prep.  But it was never called a prep school at Highgate, but other public schools called them prep schools.  It was called Highgate Junior School. So that when you went there, it helped to ens
ure that people stayed on and didn\rquote t nip off to Eton or somewhere more prestigious!  (LAUGHS)
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5975301 Ray:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 Can you say a bit more about the kind of social circle that - you talk about neighbours. I mean, was it very much a Jewish community? 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5975301 Ronald:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 Oh - oh yes.  
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5975301 Ray:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 Were your parents sociable in inviting people into the home?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5975301 Ronald:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 Oh, very much so, yes.  Yes.  And the Warm Lane Synagogue is within walking distance, and there was a Jewish butcher on the corner of the road, and several Jewish gr
ocers and greengrocers on Cricklewood Broadway.  It was second only to Golders Green \endash  it\rquote s very close to Golders Green, of course \endash  and it was people who did }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\ul\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 well}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348  moved to Cricklewood, and people who did }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\ul\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 very well}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 , like my father\rquote 
s brother, moved to Golders Green, where the houses had bigger gardens and more rooms and so on.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5975301 Ray:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 It\rquote s not really relevant to what we\rquote re talking about, but how the devil did they get the fuel to get a chauffeur during the War?  What was the fiddle that \'85?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5975301 Ronald:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 Oh, it wasn\rquote 
t a fiddle.  My father had an official petrol ration, first of all to get to his business in London, and secondly to his razor blade factory, which was in Slough, and the razor blade factory wasn\rquote 
t making razor blades, it was making armaments. [The wholesale warehouse was on several floors and two of these had also been transformed into war material factories \'93womanned\'94
 by East End women who worked part time at relatively small presses and the like.]
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5975301 Ray:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 Okay.  Well, I\rquote d like to pursue that at great length, but I think Paul would get cross if I stayed too long on that area \endash  but I\rquote 
m just personally very interested!  So what we\rquote re interested in now is how your schoolboy mind was developing, and what was interesting you at school?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5975301 Ronald:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 Well, I started t
he Labour Club!  (LAUGHS)  And I did very well.  I went up into the main school when I reached the right age, which, I suppose, was  10 or 11, and started doing natural science [in preparation for either University College Hospital from which my eldest br
other had qualified.]. 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5975301 Ray:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 Was there a sharp division between arts and science?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5975301 Ronald:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 Oh yes, very much.  There were all sorts of divisions!  (LAUGHS)  There was a science stream with Science 6A and Science 6B at the top of it, and there were all the 
usual geographies and histories and things which everyone does.  Everyone did the whole curriculum, but if you were intending to be a doctor, which is what John had decided I ought to be, you automatically went up the science stream.  And then much later,
 when I reached sort of 11 or 12, John thought it would be a good idea for me to go to Cambridge, and so it was agreed - and my father could afford it \endash  so I sat the Cambridge Examinations, but I didn\rquote 
t get a Scholarship, but I did get a place.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5975301 Ray:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 Yes, but that\rquote s later on, though.  17 or 18 would it be?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5975301 Ronald:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 Oh no.  Would it?  No, no, it would be \'85 I went in 1947, so yes, I would have been 17 when I went, yes.  Which was quite young actually.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5975301 Ray:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 I don\rquote t know what the system was then.  Presumably you had to do your \lquote A\rquote  Levels? 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5975301 Ronald:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 [Not as such.]  There was a thing called \'93Higher Certificate\'94.  You did \'93Higher Certificate\'94
, and if you wanted to go to Oxford or Cambridge, you had to get the top grade in all the [subjects]. 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5975301 Ray:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 Plus Latin?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5975301 Ronald:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 Plus Latin, yes, in every Higher\rquote s subject.  But I didn\rquote t have \endash  said he, immodestly \endash  any difficulty in doing this!  (LAUGHS)
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5975301 Ray:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 So obviously you were well regarded at Highgate.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5975301 Ronald:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 Yes, well, we didn\rquote t know, we only discovered, later, that H
ighgate actually had a quota for Jewish children.  I discovered it, because one day the Headmaster sent for me, and said, \'93It doesn\rquote t really look good when people are considering coming to the School, that some boys don\rquote 
t go in to morning prayers.  I think the best thing would be if you and Kessel\'94 - there was another boy - \'93started a Jewish Society, and then when we\rquote re having prayers, you can have your own meetings\'94
.  And so this was done.  [Kessel is now a doctor in Devon, where he stayed after the war and Highgate\rquote s return to London from Westward Ho.]
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5975301 Ray:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 Because I was going to ask you whether going to Highgate enlarged your social circle outside the world of the synagogue, because obviously the majority of boys there were not Jewish?

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5975301 Ronald:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 
No, when the Jewish Society was - there were disputed versions of this, but this is my version (LAUGHS) - when the Jewish Society was formed, the Headmaster sent for me, and there\rquote 
s a very wealthy family, who are still in Golders Green, who say it was their son they sent for \endash  which it wasn\rquote t!  (LAUGHS)
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5975301 Ray:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 Okay, right.  But you got in first!
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5975301 Ronald:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 And the Jewish Society has separate meetings, but the problem was Wednesday, because Prayer Meetings, normally, were only five minutes on most days of the w
eek, but on Wednesday there was half an hour of religious instruction or services before school, and school started a bit later on. 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5975301 Ray:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 What was the subject you took your Scholarship Exam to Cambridge in?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5975301 Ronald:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 I didn\rquote t get a Scholarship [but Higher School Certificate and then a 2:1 in Natural Sciences in my degree]. 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5975301 Ray:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 No, no, but you took the exam, you said?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5975301 Ronald:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 Yeah, I did it in Natural Sciences. Yes, and I was accepted.  Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5975301 Ray:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 But what did you actually read?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5975301 Ronald:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
