\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5975301 Ronald:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 Liberal Rabbi, and it was a terrible shock, this defeat, because I was so much more popular than John, because he was sort of prissy and \'85 (LAUGHS) 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5975301 Ray:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 What was the style of life, it was convivial, personally, in your undergraduate days?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5975301 Ronald:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 It wasn\rquote t terribly convivial, but I obviously drank a lot of beer, like everybody else!  And, yeah, I had friends in the Medical School \endash 
 well, in pre-medical. But of course, Cambridge made a big thing about that their medical students were taught the same science as everyone else, they didn\rquote 
t have a thing special until the last year, when they prepared for, was it called Common Entrance?  No.  There was a Common Entrance exam, anyway, for the Medical Schools, and so, in due course, the other thing, a cr
ucial thing, was that everyone had to stay in Cambridge three years, so you had to find something to do in the third year after you\rquote d done your anatomy and physiology and natural science Tripos, and so in the third year, under John\rquote 
s influence, I did anthropology.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5975301 Ray:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 Who taught you?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5975301 Ronald:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 
The real answer is nobody, actually.  We taught ourselves! (LAUGHS) But the Head of Department was called Hutton, Professor Hutton, who owned the naked Nagas.  He was the first person \endash  I think he was the second, actually \endash 
 his tutor at Cambridge did the first study of the Nagas, and then Hutton carried them on.  And the physical anthropologist, called Jack Trevor, who I saw quite a lot of, because it was terribly easy for me, you see, because I\rquote d done anatomy and ph
ysiology in great detail, much more detail than the physical anthropologists did. 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5975301 Ray:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 But it wasn\rquote t the kind of social anthropology that we now think of, was it?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5975301 Ronald:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 Oh [no], it wasn\rquote t.  But you had to do both social and physical anthropology, as it was called then, now it\rquote 
s called biological anthropology.  And so I did that, and I got an undistinguished 2:1.  So that was okay, and then it was at this point \'85
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5975301 Ray:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 What happened?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5975301 Ronald:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 I fell (LAUGHS)!
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5975301 Ray:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 Now we\rquote ve got a crucial point!  Here you are, 1950, graduating.  What about military service?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5975301 Ronald:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 Well, I was C4, or whatever is the lowest. I had asthma. So that wasn\rquote t [an obstacle]. 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5975301 Ray:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 Anyway, this is an important critical transition now.  You graduate from Cambridge.  What now?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5975301 Ronald:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 
Well, it happened before that, actually, that I read around anthropology quite a lot, and I found this character called Gluckman, whose work I liked very much, partly because of the influence of dialectical materialism
 on it, and partly because he was really very very interesting.  And so I asked Professor Hutton \endash  who was a very remote person, actually - I can\rquote 
t even remember what his first name was!  We never referred to him as anything except for [his surname] which was quite unusual for the rest of the Departments, actually.  And, anyway, I came across the work of Gluckman\rquote 
s, and I read this, and I decided this was the guy I\rquote d like to work with.  And so I asked Hutton, and he said, \'93Terrible fellow!\'94  (LAUGHS)  \'93Wouldn\rquote t have anything to do with him if I was you!\'94
  Because Hutton was about to retire, and he was quite overtly anti-Semitic, and he was worried about who was going to succeed him, and he didn\rquote t want to be succeeded by a Jew \endash  and he did not make any secret
 of this, and so when I asked for Gluckman to be invited to give a talk, it was just ignored.  So I asked one of the junior lecturers, and I remember it was a woman, but I don\rquote t know who it was, and she said, \'93
No, Hutton will never agree to Gluckman coming on a visit\'94.  So I wrote to Gluckman, and I said, \'93I\rquote ve read your paper on the bridge}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
