\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5975301 Ray:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 When you look back on it, what do you think the best thing is that you\rquote ve done during your time at Keele?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5975301 Ronald:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 Oh, I did quite a lot, actually.  I didn\rquote t want to come to Keele at all.  I regarded Keele as a silly bourgeois mistake, that it ought never to have \'85
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5975301 Ray:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 How did it happen?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5975301 Ronald:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 Well, I was coming home from Zambia, wasn\rquote t I?  Yes.  And I was going to be interviewed at Lancaster, because the wife who went off with the guerrilla leader 
\endash  who I didn\rquote t know had gone off - I mean, one of the reasons she went off was that she never saw me, because I was being Dean (LAUGHS) - Dean, and that!  And so I didn\rquote t actually realise I hadn\rquote 
t got that wife, when I came back from Africa!  So I was intending to go to Lancaster, where she comes from, and live in the bosom of her family. But the Vice-Chancellor of Keele, who\rquote d read an article that I wrote \endash  I can\rquote 
t remember which it was \endash  and he was a sociologist for education, wrote to me in Zambia, and said, \'93Will you call on the way?  We\rquote ve got a vacancy.  We\rquote re going to establish sociology, and we\rquote d like you to come and do it\'94
.  And my first answer was, \'93No.  I want to go to Lancaster\'94.  And then he said, \'93Well, Keele\rquote s on the way to Lancaster, why don\rquote t you call on your way?\'94  And so I called and to my \'85 (LAUGHS)  And anyway, I came and there wasn
\rquote t really any discussion, it had all been fixed up in advance, and I just saw I think it was the Vice-Chancellor, who hadn\rquote t met me. The Vice-Chancellor was an educationist who was very interested in sociology, and 
he thought that - quite correctly, I think - that Keele would never succeed unless they had a Department of Sociology, and he couldn\rquote 
t find anyone that he thought would do it, and he knew that I had a lot of administrative experience. [He also wanted to avoid anyone from LSE.]
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5975301 Ray:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 You were a professor to a New University.  You had a considerable influence on what kind of sociology was going to be taught \endash  that\rquote s evident \endash  and you\rquote 
re coming to it as an anthropologist with experience of South Wales miners, 
and running many Zambian academic institutions.  So what kind of experience would you hope that the students who came through your Department, what kind of a sociology would you hope that they\rquote d acquire?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5975301 Ronald:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 Well, I think this is actually a real description of the situation. Sociology hadn\rquote 
t been much developed at Keele.  There was one professor before me, he was called Howard Jones, and went to Cardiff, who actually didn\rquote t know very much sociology.  He was basically a social worker, and he had been di
sastrous, which is why the Vice-Chancellor was behaving like this, because he wanted to get someone to replace him, and then sack him, which is, in fact, what he did.  And he went to Cardiff, where he\rquote d come from, and he didn\rquote 
t live a great deal longer.  H
e was older than me anyway.  So what I set out to do when I came, was to try to develop a Sociology Department which was concerned with society as it was, and [so that the students] studied it, and did it for themselves.  And so I abolished all lectures a
n
d replaced them with discussion groups, which I, or another member of the Department chaired, and I did it in such a way that while other members of the Department stayed with one discussion group, I moved around them all. And what I did is, I asked these
 - there were, I think, eight people in each group, and before I went to them the first time, they had to think of a topic that they wanted to study - \'93the sociology of\'94
 - with a certain amount of discouragement from it being social work!  (LAUGHS)  Because
 what I saw my job as being, and what the Vice-Chancellor wanted, was shifting it away from a Department which taught you what to do if a woman came to you and told you she wasn\rquote 
t married, and was expecting a baby.  They were just dealing with practical pr
oblems at a very pragmatic level.  And so when I met a class - and eventually when some other lecturers came, they did the same, because I told them they had to! - when I went to a class, I asked them to talk for a bit with me about things that they thoug
ht they might learn from sociology. Then I told them to go away and talk amongst themselves.  And the next time I met them, to tell me what they would like to study.  And they obviously agreed to do this, because they weren\rquote 
t in a position to refuse!  (LAUGHS)  And also it was very much in line with the general ideology of Keele, with self-directed studies.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5975301 Ray:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 How long did those procedures continue?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5975301 Ronald:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 Really until I left. I think so.  I wouldn\rquote t be sure.  I\rquote d have to check on that.  But it worked v
ery well.  I mean, the Vice-Chancellor had backed me very strongly, but a lot of other people on the staff, in general, thought that the students weren\rquote t capable of doing this.  But they did. 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5975301 Ray:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
