he West Indies, all but half a mile!  (LAUGHS)  At that point I was told I wasn\rquote t going to be allowed to land, and had to stay on the boat, so I never actually set foot in the West Indies.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 PAUL:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 
Who was it said that you couldn\rquote t land?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5975301 Ronald:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 The Immigration Officer of Barbados.  He had been informed, from London, that I was a dangerous Communist, and it wasn\rquote 
t safe for me to land.  Did I tell you about [Arthur Lewis] the Professor of Economics in Manchester?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 PAUL:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 I\rquote m not sure.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5975301 Ronald:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 Oh well, I\rquote ll tell you now.  (LAUGHS)  He was Arthur Lewis, who is famous.  I don\rquote t know if you\rquote ve heard of him \endash 
 probably not these days.  He was a famous economist, a West Indian, and he was very angry at my going to the West Indies because he felt this was reducing the
 West Indians to the level of Africans if anthropologists went to study them. Whereas Max Gluckman\rquote s whole idea, and Eli Devons, who was Max\rquote 
s great friend, who was a famous economist also, their idea was that anthropologists should study people anywhere in the world, and this idea that anthropologists should only be interested in Africans or \'93natives\'94
 was completely wrong.  And the suspicion, in Manchester, was that \'85 Arthur Lewis had pulled strings and arranged with the West Indian High Commission that I wouldn\rquote 
t be allowed, because he felt that being studied by an anthropologist reduced you to the level of being a native.  (LAUGHS)  Strange! Strange!
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 PAUL:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 
Absolutely!  Yes. So then you came to Wales instead?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5975301 Ronald:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 That\rquote s right.  I wanted to modify a bit about this because this relates to something which I think \endash  which is somewhere in the papers \endash 
 which I think you quote.   You say that interviewing people is not participant observation, and I disagree with that. (LAUGHS}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764 )}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348  Quite strongly in fact, becaus
e successful interviewing means that both sides, the person being interviewed and the interviewer, actually almost change themselves into each other in the course of the conversation.  If it\rquote 
s to be successful, the person being interviewed must, to some extent, identify and understand where the interviewer is coming from, and so it\rquote 
s a form of participant observation which is created in the process.  That seems, to me, quite important in writing about these things.  So that it never occurred to me at the time, or, I think, to Max, that I wouldn\rquote 
t be doing participant observation, because I\rquote d be asking formal questions.  Can I persuade you to accept \'85 (LAUGHS)
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 PAUL:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 No, that\rquote 
s all right!  
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5975301 Ronald:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 So to interview someone, you have to get to know them.  And 
how I learnt this is actually quite significant, because when I started on the farm, first of all I lodged for a very short time in the village, and then I actually went to live in the farm of my first informant.  Yeah.  Now, in order for us to talk to ea
ch other, we really had to get inside the other person\rquote s way of life, so that one isn\rquote t interviewing from outside.  One is getting right inside.  And one of the things which \endash  it isn\rquote 
t in here [in the interview transcript], actually, because I only thought this out afterwards \endash  is my intention in going to the farm and working from there, was to do all my work in the farm.  But, of course, since the farmer wasn\rquote 
t just taking me as a lodger, but part of the job of being a farmer in North Wales was, in fact, le
tting out your spare rooms in the summer to visitors.  So when the summer came, I had to get out from the farm to make room for his regular visitors, because the same people came every year to all these farms. As again, Max and Emrys [Peters] did, they ha
d particular farms in North Wales, not in this village, as we avoided those deliberately, they had particular places where they took their family in the summer. So that this kind of interviewing wasn\rquote 
t just the thing that you did in an afternoon or in a couple of hours, you moved in and became part of \'85 And most of the farmers \endash  well, it\rquote s probably rash to say \'93most of the farmers\'94 \endash 
 but certainly many of the farmers in North Wales, at that time, had got part of their income by having people come and either 
camp or live in spare outbuildings and so on, for a period in the summer, and the same people came back every year. So that my role as an anthropologist and interviewer living in a farm wasn\rquote 
t something new, it was something that quite a lot of people did, although they didn\rquote t usually write it up.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 PAUL:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 
I see.  Did you keep notes, then?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5975301 Ronald:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 I\rquote m sure I did, yes, but where on earth \'85!  (LAUGHS)
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 PAUL:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 That\rquote 
s another question!  And you were learning Welsh while you were on the farm, were you?
