\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5975301 Ronald:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 
Yes.  Well, I started learning Welsh before I went, and in the house in the village where I lived at first, and continually through the whole process of the research.  I was never a very fluent Welsh speaker, but it was more important that I could underst
a
nd in depth, what people were saying to me, than they should understand, in depth, what I was saying to them, as long as what I said was convincing enough for them to go on answering questions.  I mean, they were sort of baffled and amused, and slightly f
l
attered. And the vicar put in a good word - (LAUGHS) a good word for me, and helped to explain what anthropologists did, and why it was good that anthropologists and sociologists should know what they did, because it meant they would understand what their
 problems were, and so on.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 PAUL:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 
So in terms of observation and doing these informal interviews, you did that on the farm - and then where else?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5975301 Ronald:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 Oh well, first of all I lived in the village, and then Mrs. Evans said, \'93Oh well, you should go and ta
lk to Farmer So and So, because they always take in summer visitors as holiday makers, they might as well take you as well\'94
.  (LAUGHS)  I mean, the people who stayed in village houses would perhaps stay for a week or ten days or less, whereas the people wh
o went to the farms, came back year after year, and their children went there. Of course, the farmers had fishing rights and hunting rights and so on, so that they could have a good sort of active holiday.  And people like Max Gluckman and Eli Devons, and
 
[Arthur Lewis] the Professor of Economics, had done this for many a year.  And my argument would be that in order even to do this, never mind write about them afterwards, you needed to do some kind of anthropological study to know when to go, when not to 
go, because the farmers \endash  and the farmer\rquote s wife \endash 
 were going to be too busy with the cattle or whatnot, to deal with you - and where you could go fishing, and what fishing rights the farmer had and so on.  So I think this must have been written about!  
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 PAUL:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 
But you also focused, I think, on the Football Club, isn\rquote t that right?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5975301 Ronald:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 Oh yes, that\rquote s right.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 PAUL:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 
And what did you do with them?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5975301 Ronald:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 Well, I think I kept them - all these people hated writing, especially (LAUGHS), especially in English!
  Yes, especially in English.  So they were glad to have someone who would take notes at meetings, and produce Minutes which they could then use with their funders or with their members. Because farmers, on the whole, didn\rquote 
t like writing at all.  They could all read and write \endash  at least in Welsh \endash  but they were very self-conscious, so people would show me their invoices or letters they\rquote 
d written to visitors who were going to come, and ask, you know, if the English was all right \endash  because they were very self-conscious.
