\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5975301 Ronald:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 Yeah.  So they catered for them.  There were two quite good hotels in Glyn, so I went there to drink, but apart from that I didn\rquote 
t have much to do with them. But it was an essential part of farmers\rquote  income to have people come on their land either to shoot or as walkers, during the summer. Because, agriculturally, it wasn\rquote 
t a terribly prosperous area, and any extra cash you could get by your wife giving afternoon teas, or you renting a stretch of your stream to a fisherman, and so on, was all part of the necessities of life.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 PAUL:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 Well, I think that
\rquote s very helpful about your North Welsh study.  But I was looking at the series of things that you\rquote ve done, and was reminded that the next one you did was actually a steelworkers village. I\rquote 
d be really interested to hear you say something about that, because we\rquote ve got Michael Fogarty, wasn\rquote t it?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5975301 Ronald:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 (LAUGHS)  Michael P. Fogarty, yeah!  
Yes, he was quite a character.  He was Professor of Industrial Relations at Cardiff, and a pioneer of - how shall I put it?  Sort of open industrial relations done by actually going to factories and talking to the workers and managers, rather than looking
 
at the statistics of numbers of days lost through strikes and so on.  And he was also - which made him popular with some, and a person of great suspicion with others (LAUGHS), a very devout, practising Roman Catholic, which is not always a good thing to b
e in Wales!  Even in Cardiff!  But he was also a well-known pioneer of a sociological approach to work and employment problems.  Very active, not only in the Catholic Church, but I suspect probably in the Labour Party, but certainly in local politics.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 PAUL:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 
And what was your role in that study, then?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5975301 Ronald:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 Oh, I gave some lectures and did some teaching, but the research I was doing wasn\rquote t really related.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 PAUL:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 
Oh, that was when you were working for the Union, was it?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5975301 Ronald:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 Yeah, well, I worked for the Union, but I also did some studies of mining villages and so on before.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 PAUL:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 On your own, was that 
\endash  the mining villages?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5975301 Ronald:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 Yeah, yes.  On my own in the sense I was the only person there, that was actually there asking questions, but Michael Fogarty, as an expert in industrial relations 
\endash  his field was industrial relations \endash  was very glad to have me do this, as were the local miners, because they knew I was on their side, so to speak, because I also worked for the Union.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 PAUL:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348  But you didn\rquote 
t live in those villages, did you?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5975301 Ronald:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 No.  No, I lived in Cardiff.  I had - I\rquote m not quite sure what to call it - (LAUGHS) - a high social position in Cardiff, but I was quite a figure in the town 
\endash  not through any merit of mine \endash 
 partly because my then wife was related, as a niece, to the Headmistresses of all the most important schools in the area, who were, especially the Heads, very influential in Cardiff.  And also through Michael Fogarty I had a link to all the Company Dire
ctors and people who were important in industry.  And also as a former official of the Miners\rquote  Union \endash 
 I was Education Officer of the South Wales Miners, I was well-known there.  And I also had some other very useful connections who were related, somehow, to very important people, not only in Wales, but also in London, because they were Welsh women.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 PAUL:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 
Did anything come out of your research in the mining villages?  Did you publish a book?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5975301 Ronald:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 I didn\rquote t publish a book, no.  I really can\rquote t remember.  I probably wrote the odd articles.  Oh yes, I did have a book, of course, but it doesn\rquote 
t have my name on it, I have got a copy of the final version, which was }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 The Life of Arthur Horner}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 , who was the leader of the miners. The actual donkey work was done by t
he daughter of the Professor of Economics at Keele, and they turned out to be a very tragic family, because the father, the mother, the daughter, and another member of the family, all died in about two months.  They\rquote 
d left Keele, and were living in South Wales, and they - I mean, it\rquote s not possible to make any analysis - they all died with different things, but they just all died in a very short time. And she left behind a manuscript - which I\rquote 
ve got upstairs - on the history of mining, it\rquote s quite vast, which was published just after she\rquote d already died - she was very young \endash  which was on the life of Arthur Horner.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 PAUL:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 
And what was your role there, then?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5975301 Ronald:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 Well, I wouldn\rquote t want this to be published, but it was really re-writing it actually, because i
t had to be done very very quickly, because she was already known to be dying, and Lawrence and Wishart had agreed to publish it, and we just managed to get it to them before she died. Because although she was very good, she was economics, and industrial 
relations, she didn\rquote t write very well. So if you\rquote re interested, I\rquote ve got a copy of it.  I\rquote ve got a copy of the final version, which I worked on, I haven\rquote 
t actually got a copy of the final printed published version, because I was waiting for the price to go down (LAUGHS) and it never did!  It\rquote 
s the size of two Ph.D.s.  It was a book that was published by Lawrence and Wishart to distribute to a list of people who they knew were interested in it.  It wasn\rquote t the sort of book that goes to every bookshop.  I think
 Keele Bookshop sold a couple of copies because everyone knew her and her father and mother, and some people in Cardiff bought it, but it wasn\rquote t exactly a best-seller.  I\rquote ll show it to you later and you can see how it couldn\rquote 
t have been a best-seller!  (LAUGHS)  It\rquote s [several inches] thick, and totally detailed.  So it\rquote s a book that if they can find, it will be very valuable to people who are writing on the rise and fall of the coal mining industry, but it
\rquote s not bedside reading!
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 PAUL:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 Maybe we could jump o
n, now, to - because you mentioned about working in Africa, and you did, I think, a community study of a place called Materlo with Joyce Leeson? 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5975301 Ronald:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 That\rquote s right, yes.
