\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 PAUL:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 
Is it the same kind of method? 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5975301 Ronald:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 Yes.  I don\rquote t think we actually lived in Materlo.  We did - yes, we did, actually.  Both Joyce and I were very productive in Africa. I was supposed to \endash 
 we were, I think we were married - if we weren\rquote t married, we were just about to get married: and we were supposed to go and live in Lancaster with Joyce\rquote 
s parents. But I never actually got there, Because I was sort of Poo-Bah in Africa, people tended to be, because they were very short of people who were educated, and so I was Dean of Medicine, Chairman of the Universi
ty Hospital Building Committee. And Joyce and I had a house built for us in Materlo Township, where there were virtually no Europeans living.  The only people who lived there were people who were either workers or people like us who\rquote 
d had a house built for
 them because they were carrying out some function for the government.  But we were both terribly busy, and so apart from the night, we hardly met. And she used to go and help the South African National Congress people who were living in Materlo Township,
 and she fell in love with one of them. So when we left Africa to come back to Britain, she said, \'93Oh well\'94 - actually, she was going to marry Zola.  (LAUGHS)
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 PAUL:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 Zola?
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid1905312 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5975301 Ronald:}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 
Zola he was called.  And she was going to divorce me and marry Zola, and, \'93Goodbye.  It hasn\rquote t been particularly (LAUGHS) nice knowing you\'94
, which was a bit - it was, well actually, it was entirely unexpected at first, but then I realised it had been brewing for a long time.  And so when I came to Keele, she didn\rquote t come with me.  
In fact, I was offered the job at Keele, and was going to refuse it because I was supposed to be going to Lancaster in a Department there, I can\rquote 
t remember what Department it was, and Joyce was going to resume her career as a medical teacher.  But then I received two letters on about the same day \endash  one from the Vice-Chancellor of Keele, saying \'93
We would like you to be our Professor of Sociology.  Would you like to come?\'94  So I replied \'93No\'94.  And then I had a letter from Joyce saying, \'93I\rquote m going to marry Zola and live with my parents in Lancaster\'94
. (LAUGHS) So instead of coming back to a post in Lancaster, which I\rquote d}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764  expected, I came to Keele.  \'85 }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15155764\charrsid8024348 I don\rquote t think it\rquote s terribly relevant to what we\rquote re doing here, but there was a sort of crisis in sociology at that 
time, because all the sociologists that were qualified and available to take university posts, had been trained at the LSE by the same small group of teachers who are not well-regarded outside sociology, so Keele very much wanted a sociologist, but didn
\rquote t want to have one who\rquote d been trained at LSE.  The reason they wanted to have a sociologist was that Lord Lindsey thought they ought to have social sciences, so the Vice-Chancellor wrote to me and said, \'93
Will you come and be our first Professor of Sociology?\'94  And I said, \'93No, I\rquote m going (LAUGHS) to Lancaster\'94. And then a couple of days later, when I had discovered the real [situation] the Vice-Chancellor said, \'93
You can stop off at Manchester airport on your way to Lancaster, and I\rquote ll talk to you\'94.  By the tim
e that day came, it was clear that Joyce was going to divorce me and marry Zola, and so I came to Manchester airport, and was duly met by the Vice-Chancellor, and  given the Chair in Sociology \endash  just like that!  (LAUGHS)  That\rquote 
s the way people used to do things in those days!  (LAUGHS) ... 
